# Question 1: Define data structure and explain types. Discuss time and space complexity with examples. Compare best, worst, and average cases for common operations on arrays and linked lists.

## Definition of Data Structure.
Data structure is a method of organizing, storing, and managing data efficiently.  
It helps in performing operations like insertion, deletion, searching, and sorting.

---

## Types of Data Structure

### 1. Linear Data Structure
Elements are arranged sequentially.  
Examples:
- Array  
- Linked List  
- Stack  
- Queue  

### 2. Non-Linear Data Structure
Elements are arranged hierarchically.  
Examples:
- Tree  
- Graph  

### 3. Static Data Structure
Size is fixed.  
Memory is allocated before execution.  

Example:
- Array  

### 4. Dynamic Data Structure
Size changes during execution.  

Example:
- Linked List  

---

## Time Complexity
Time complexity measures the time required by an algorithm to execute.

Examples:
- Linear Search → O(n)  
- Binary Search → O(log n)  
- Array Access → O(1)  

---

## Space Complexity
Space complexity measures the amount of memory used by an algorithm.

Examples:
- Array storing n elements → O(n)  
- Using only variables → O(1)  

---

## Best Case
Minimum execution time required by an algorithm.

Example:
Searching first element in array.

---

## Worst Case
Maximum execution time required by an algorithm.

Example:
Searching last element in array.

---

## Average Case
Average execution time required by an algorithm.

Example:
Searching middle element in array.

---

## Comparison of Arrays and Linked Lists

| Operation | Array | Linked List |
|------------|--------|-------------|
| Access | O(1) | O(n) |
| Insertion | O(n) | O(1) |
| Deletion | O(n) | O(1) |
| Searching | O(n) | O(n) |

---

## Conclusion
Data structures help in efficient data storage and processing. Choosing the correct data structure improves performance.
